auditok Changelog
=================

Version 0.5.1
-------------

- ``energy_threshold`` (``-e``) takes a number. Automatic threshold
  estimation is selected with ``validator`` (``-V``): ``"otsu"``,
  ``"percentile"`` or ``"pXX"``. A ``validator``, when given, takes
  precedence and ``energy_threshold`` is overlooked.

- Fix automatic thresholding on digitally silent input: estimation on an
  input with no non-silent windows now yields no events (previously the
  whole input was returned as one event). On live input, a silent
  calibration window falls back to ``min_energy_threshold`` and
  detection continues.

- Document which modes stream: a fixed ``energy_threshold`` and the
  webrtc validator emit events from the first frame (with compressed
  input, while ffmpeg is still decoding); offline estimation reads the
  whole input before detection starts.

Version 0.5.0
-------------

Breaking changes:

- ``sample_width=4`` now means 32-bit *float* audio (see below). Previous
  versions interpreted it as 32-bit integer, which never worked correctly:
  energies computed on int32 amplitudes made the default threshold pass
  everywhere and detection collapsed into one giant event. 32-bit integer
  audio is now rejected explicitly; load such files through ffmpeg (with
  ``sw=2`` or ``sw=4``) to convert.

New features:

- Add 32-bit float audio support (``sample_width=4``) across the library:
  loading and saving float32 WAV files (``WAVE_FORMAT_IEEE_FLOAT`` and
  ``WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE`` headers), ffmpeg I/O via ``pcm_f32le``,
  microphone capture and playback via sounddevice's native float32, and the
  CLI (``-w 4``). Float32 samples are scaled to the int16 amplitude
  reference internally, so ``energy_threshold`` keeps exactly the same
  meaning for all sample widths — no retuning needed.

- Add a minimal RIFF/WAVE header parser used for all WAV reading: fixes
  reading ``WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE`` files (e.g., WAVs produced by ffmpeg)
  on Python < 3.12, where the stdlib ``wave`` module raises
  ``wave.Error: unknown format: 65534``.

- Add automatic energy thresholding: estimate the energy threshold from the
  input's energy distribution instead of using a fixed value. Use
  ``energy_threshold="auto"`` for the default method, or name the method
  with ``validator="otsu"`` (balanced, histogram-based),
  ``validator="percentile"`` (noise floor + margin, recall-oriented) or
  ``validator="pXX"`` (noise floor read at the XXth percentile;
  ``"percentile"`` is an alias for ``"p10"``). Available in ``split``,
  ``trim`` and ``fix_pauses``, and on the CLI as ``-e auto`` /
  ``-V otsu|percentile|pXX`` (the resolved value is printed to stderr).
  For offline input the whole signal is used for estimation and is never
  decoded twice: compressed audio is decoded once and tokenized from
  memory; ``large_file`` (wav/raw) inputs are estimated with a chunked
  low-memory pass and re-read from disk. The building blocks are public:
  ``auditok.signal.compute_frame_energies`` and
  ``auditok.signal.estimate_energy_threshold`` (with per-method parameters
  such as ``percentile`` and ``margin``).

- Automatic thresholding works with live input (microphone, standard
  input) and ``AudioReader`` input too: the threshold is calibrated on the
  first ``calibration_dur`` seconds of the stream (default 3) and kept
  unchanged afterwards; the calibration audio is buffered and replayed, so
  events starting during calibration are not lost. The calibrated
  threshold is ``max(min_energy_threshold, estimate)`` (default 40 dB;
  live input only — offline estimation is protected by excluding digitally
  silent windows instead), so a calibration window containing only
  background noise or silence cannot yield a meaningless threshold. Both
  knobs are exposed on the CLI as ``-U``/``--calibration-duration`` and
  ``-y``/``--min-energy-threshold``, and the resolved threshold is echoed
  after calibration. Passing an explicit numeric ``energy_threshold`` (or
  ``-e``) bypasses estimation entirely.

- Add ``WebRTCVADValidator`` (``auditok.validators``): use the WebRTC
  voice activity detector as the frame-level decider inside auditok's
  event machinery, to detect *speech* specifically rather than any audio
  activity. Available as ``validator="webrtc"`` / ``"webrtc:N"`` (N =
  aggressiveness in [0, 3]) on ``split``, ``trim`` and ``fix_pauses``, on
  the CLI as ``-V webrtc[:N]``, or as a class for full control (subframe
  duration, decision aggregation, channel selection). Works with live
  input. Requires the new optional dependency group ``auditok[webrtcvad]``
  (the ``webrtcvad-wheels`` package); the core stays numpy-only.

- CLI: explicitly given ``-r``/``-w``/``-c`` are now forwarded for
  compressed file input, letting ffmpeg convert the audio on the fly
  (e.g., ``auditok audio.mp3 -r 16000 -V webrtc``). Default values are
  still ignored for file input, preserving the original format.

Improvements:

- Make plotting tests independent of matplotlib/numpy versions (assert on
  figure contents instead of comparing pixel-exact images).

Documentation:

- Overhaul the README: table of contents, restructured sections, and a
  fact-check pass.
- Switch the documentation theme to shibuya, with dark (monokai) code
  blocks.
- Refresh the project logo.

Bug fixes:

- Fix a potential deadlock in ``FFmpegAudioSource`` error handling: when
  reading the decoder's output fails, ffmpeg is now killed before its
  stderr is read, so it cannot block on a full stdout pipe.

Packaging and metadata:

- Add Python 3.15 to the CI test matrix.


Version 0.4.2
-------------

Improvements:

- Allow ``max_trailing_silence`` to exceed ``max_silence``: after the event
  boundary is decided (at ``max_silence``), additional silent frames are
  collected past the boundary up to ``max_trailing_silence``. Collection stops
  as soon as a new valid frame is detected, so separate events are not merged.
  This lets you use a small ``max_silence`` for tight event boundaries while
  keeping enough trailing audio to preserve natural fadeouts. The same option
  is exposed on the CLI as ``-g``/``--max-trailing-silence``.

Bug fixes:

- Fix 1-frame gap in leading silence between consecutive events. The silent
  frame that triggered the transition into ``SILENCE`` was previously dropped
  instead of being seeded into the leading buffer for the next token, causing
  an unavoidable 1-frame gap regardless of ``max_leading_silence``. Trailing
  frames trimmed by ``max_trailing_silence`` are now also seeded into the
  leading buffer of the next token.


Version 0.4.1
-------------

Bug fixes:

- Fix CLI forcing default ``-r``/``-w``/``-c`` on file input via ``FFmpegAudioSource``
- Fix Ctrl+C crash and audio glitches during playback with ``-E``
- Quit correctly when ``-B`` is specified for audio playback with progress bar

Improvements:

- Refactor command line code and tests
- Show an error message when a command line argument appears more than once
- Make CLI help text 80-column max


Version 0.4.0
-------------

Breaking changes:

- Drop Python 3.7 support (EOL since June 2023)
- Drop pydub dependency; ffmpeg is now required directly for non-WAV/raw formats
- Replace pyaudio with sounddevice for microphone input
- Remove deprecated ``AudioRegion.meta`` accessor (use ``.start`` / ``.end``)
- Remove deprecated ``AudioRegion.samples`` property (use ``.numpy()``)
- Make ``split()``, ``trim()``, ``split_and_plot()`` keyword-only after the first positional argument
- Remove ``dataset`` module; split ``core.py`` into ``audio.py`` and ``core.py``
- Remove ``setup.py``; migrate to ``pyproject.toml``

New features:

- Add ``FFmpegAudioSource``: streams audio from an ffmpeg subprocess pipe, ~2x faster than pydub's temp-file approach
- Add ``trim()`` to remove leading and trailing silence from audio
- Add ``fix_pauses()`` / ``remove_pauses()`` to normalize pauses between audio events
- Add ``max_leading_silence`` parameter to ``split()``, ``trim()``, and ``StreamTokenizer`` to preserve natural sound onsets
- Add ``max_trailing_silence`` parameter to control trailing silence independently of ``max_silence``; deprecate ``drop_trailing_silence``
- ``split()`` accepts ``max_dur=None`` (or ``float("inf")``) for unlimited event length
- ``FFmpegAudioSource`` accepts ``sampling_rate``, ``sample_width``, ``channels`` for on-the-fly conversion
- ``from_file()`` forwards ``sr``/``sw``/``ch`` to ``FFmpegAudioSource``
- Use ffmpeg for audio export; ``save()`` accepts ``audio_codec``, ``audio_bitrate``, ``audio_quality``, ``ffmpeg_extra_args``
- ``AudioRegion._repr_html_()`` renders inline HTML5 audio player in Jupyter
- Add interactive Jupyter widget: ``split_and_plot(interactive=True)`` with Canvas waveform, clickable regions, playback controls, and time ruler
- Restructure CLI with subcommands: ``auditok split`` (default), ``auditok trim``, ``auditok fix-pauses``
- Add ``--max-leading-silence`` and ``--max-trailing-silence`` CLI options
- Add recording indicator with elapsed time for mic-based ``trim`` and ``fix-pauses``
- Make ``--drop-trailing-silence`` deprecated in CLI

Packaging and metadata:

- Migrate from ``setup.py`` to ``pyproject.toml``
- Make ``matplotlib``, ``sounddevice``, and ``tqdm`` optional (``pip install auditok[all]``)
- Update development status from Alpha to Production/Stable
- Add VAD, silence detection, and audio segmentation keywords for PyPI
- Add Python 3.14 support
- Add type annotations to public API with ``py.typed`` marker (PEP 561)
- Add mypy to pre-commit hooks

Bug fixes:

- Fix ``split()`` using ``analysis_window`` instead of actual frame duration after int truncation
- Validate ``hop_size`` and ``block_size`` in ``_OverlapAudioReader``
- Fix matplotlib plot layout: wide figure default, proper legend placement
- Fix deprecated ``AudioRegion.meta.start``/``.end`` usage in ``split_and_plot()``
- Suppress C-level ALSA/JACK/OSS warnings from PortAudio during initialization
- Fix resource leak in ``split()`` when generator is not fully consumed


Version 0.3.0
-------------

- Use `numpy` instead of the `audioop` (deprecated then removed in Python 13) for signal processing operations
- Use `pytest` instead of `genty` for tests
- Accept input of type `Path` for `split`
- Remove deprecated `ADSFactory`
- Implement `AudioRegion.join`, `make_silence` and `split_and_join_with_silence`
- Use Github Actions instead of travis for CI
- Use Codecov for tests coverage


Version 0.2.0
-------------

- Implement split function as a high-level API for tokenization
- Implement AudioRegion class for simple audio objects manipulation
- Use a much faster energy computation method (based on standard audioop module)
- Make ADSFactory deprecated
- Choose which channel(s) to use for tokenization
- Save multi-channel audio data
- Refactor code in all modules
- Use genty for tests
- Improve documentation
- Use ArgumentParser instead of OptionParser in command-line script
- Clean up command-line script and move functions and workers to dedicated modules
- Add "timestamp" placehoder to main script
- Play audio with a progress bar
- StreamSaverWorker: avoid caching data for a long time in memory, save data regularly to disk
- Use numpy style for documentation and update theme
- Ensure pep8 compliance (flake8) and formatting with black
- Add pre-commit hooks
- Change license to MIT
- Add project logo


